         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translation</head>
            <p>To Demeter and Kore, Antonia dedicated the (statue of) Aretaphila
</p><p/></div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>The dedicator names herself only by a Roman nomen, 
               apparently without filiation or a cognomen.
               It is probable that she belonged to a family of Antonii who are attested among Cyrene’s leading citizens in the first century C.E. (see index)</p> 
            <p>Aretaphila, whose statue was dedicated, apparently lived in the first half of the first century B.C.
               and played a decisive part in securing
               the overthrow of a tyrant of Cyrene (Plut. De mul. vir. no.19; Polyaenus, Strat. VIII.38),
               after which she is said to have withdrawn into private life,
               which would be compatible with engagement in a women’s cult,
               so that it may be that she was honoured here as a significant figure in the cult of Demeter and Kore.
               On the other hand, such evidence as we have seems to suggest that the city was erecting public honours
               in the Sanctuary in the first century B.C. (<ref type="inscription">C88800</ref>, <ref type="inscription">C88900</ref>, <ref type="inscription">C89000</ref>),
               perhaps always of women (although this is not certain given the condition of some texts, e.g.<ref type="inscription">C88900</ref>, <ref type="inscription">C89000</ref>);
               and Aretaphila may be honoured by Antonia for her public services which,
               no doubt, did not need to be stated.
            </p>
            
         </div>
         
